04799nam a22006855i 9781442623644DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20172001onc    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1024041252  a97814426236447 a10.3138/97814426236442doi  a(DE-B1597)483150  a(OCoLC)1005712165  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aSH224.N7W75 2001 7aHIS0060202bisacsh04a3381 aWright, Miriam, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Fishery for Modern Times :bThe State and the Industrialization of the Newfoundland Fishery, 1934-1968 /cMiriam Wright. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2017] 4cÂ©2001  a1 online resource (208 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCanadian Social History Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- t1. Introduction -- tPART I. Industrialization in Depression and Wartime: The 1930s and 1940s -- tPART II. Planning for a New Fishery: the 1950s -- tPART III. Competition for the Resource and the Consolidation of Industrialization: the 1960s -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the early 1990s, the northern cod populations off the coast of Newfoundland had become so depleted that the federal government placed a moratorium on commercial fishing. The impact was devastating, both for Newfoundland's economy and for local fishing communities. Today, although this natural resource - exploited commercially for over 500 years - appears to be returning in diminished numbers, many fisheries scientists and fishers question whether the cod will ever return to its former abundance.In A Fishery for Modern Times, Miriam Wright argues that the recent troubles in the fishery can be more fully understood by examining the rise of the industrial fishery in the mid-twentieth century. The introduction of new harvesting technologies and the emergence of 'quick freezing', in the late 1930s, eventually supplanted household production by Newfoundland's fishing families. While the new technologies increased the amount of fish caught in the northwest Atlantic, Wright argues that the state played a critical role in fostering and financing the industrial frozen fish sector. Many bureaucrats and politicians, including Newfoundland's premier, Joseph Smallwood, believed that making the Newfoundland fishery 'modern', with centralization, technology, and expertise, would transform rural society, solving deep-seated economic and social problems.A Fishery for Modern Times examines the ways in which the state, ideologies of development, and political, economic, and social factors, along with political actors and fishing company owners, contributed to the expansion of the industrial fishery from the 1930s through the 1960s. While the promised prosperity never fully materialized, the continuing reliance on approaches favouring high-tech, big capital solutions put increasing pressure on cod populations in the years that followed. As Wright concludes, 'We can no longer afford to view the fisheries resources as "property" of the state and industry, to do with it as they choose. That path had led only to devastation of the resource, economic instability, and great social upheaval.'  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aFisherieszNewfoundland and Labrador. 0aFishery managementxHistoryy20th century. 0aFishery policyzNewfoundland and LabradorxHistoryy20th century. 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Post-Confederation (1867-).2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144262364440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442623644423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442623644.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEB